{{About|the waterfall|the state park|Amicalola Falls State Park}} {{Infobox waterfall | name = Amicalola Falls | photo = Amicalola Falls.JPG | photo_width = | photo_caption = (view from the 'Reflecting Pool' at bottom) | map = USA Georgia | coordinates = {{coord|34|34|3|N|84|14|40|W|type:waterbody_scale:50000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | location = [[Dawson County, Georgia|Dawson County]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States | elevation = {{convert|1900|ft|abbr=on}} | type = Cascade | height = {{convert|729|ft|m}} | width = | height_longest = | average_width = | number_drops = | average_flow = | watercourse = Little Amicalola Creek }}
'''Amicalola Falls''' is a 729-foot (222 m) [[waterfall]] on [[Amicalola Creek]] in [[Dawson County, Georgia|Dawson County]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States. It the highest waterfall in Georgia and is considered to be one of the [[List of the Seven Natural Wonders of Georgia (U.S. state)|Seven Natural Wonders of Georgia]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Boyd|first=Brian|title=Waterfalls of the Southern Appalachians & Great Smoky Mountains|year=2001|publisher=Fern Creek Press|isbn=978-1-893651-08-1|location=Clayton, GA}}</ref> The name "Amicalola" is derived from a [[Cherokee language]] word meaning "tumbling waters".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yyMxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xDoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5700%2C4457103 | title=The Names Stayed | work=Calhoun Times and Gordon County News | date=August 29, 1990 | accessdate=29 April 2015 | pages=64}}</ref> The falls are the centerpiece of [[Amicalola Falls State Park]].<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.kenkrakow.com/gpn/a.pdf | title=Georgia Place-Names: Their History and Origins | publisher=Winship Press | author=Krakow, Kenneth K. | year=1975 | location=Macon, GA | pages=5 | isbn=0-915430-00-2}}</ref>
